<div id="review_3704903873" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3704903873" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2044938-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468979731p2/2044938.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3704903873?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/2044938-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3704903873" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7748156007931066879">Oh Mr. Jefferson, what are we going to do with you? <br/><br/>American Sphinx is my second book about the founding fathers this year, all sparked by my desire to read Hamilton after watching the musical. I still haven&apos;t gotten around to that one, but now I&apos;ve read about Adams and Jefferson! <br/><br/>I wanted to read about Jefferson after reading David McCollough&apos;s biography of John Adams because McCollough didn&apos;t present Jefferson in a very favorable light, which was surprising to me and I wanted to know if it was</span>
  <span id="freeText7748156007931066879" style="display:none">Oh Mr. Jefferson, what are we going to do with you? <br /><br />American Sphinx is my second book about the founding fathers this year, all sparked by my desire to read Hamilton after watching the musical. I still haven't gotten around to that one, but now I've read about Adams and Jefferson! <br /><br />I wanted to read about Jefferson after reading David McCollough's biography of John Adams because McCollough didn't present Jefferson in a very favorable light, which was surprising to me and I wanted to know if it was just bias on McCollough's part. <br /><br />Spoiler alert: that doesn't seem to be the case.<br /><br />I can't help but compare the Adams and Jefferson biographies, which is fair, since the men themselves were often compared and contrasted throughout their lives and throughout history. I will say though, that I prefer Adams - both the book and the person. McCollough's writing style is so engaging and he made me love and admire Adams' integrity and perseverance, despite his many foibles. Whenever Adams was mentioned throughout American Sphinx (which was not as frequently as Jefferson was mentioned throughout the Adams bio, signaling the different value each placed on the other in his own life) I felt like a mutual friend was being brought up. <br /><br />Ellis' book, on the other hand, while not poorly written by any stretch, lacks the storytelling element that can make a historical figure come to life for the reader in quite the same way. But this seems to be the essence of what the title implies - Jefferson was and is simply a difficult person to know, especially via historical details, because his actions, words and ideas were often contradictory. <br /><br />One of my main takeaways from American Sphinx is that Thomas Jefferson didn't have much of a sense of humor and took himself far too seriously. This isn't explicitly stated anywhere, but it's my strong impression, especially after reading about the amiable, somewhat jocular, Adams. Jefferson was a highly introverted idealist who dealt better with words than with people. (I actually remarked several times to my husband while reading that TJ actually reminded me quite a lot of him, except my husband is funny and does not take himself too seriously). <br /><br />Ellis makes a big point in the book about Jefferson's ability to hold two opposing ideas in his head simultaneously without feeling them to be contradictory. The biggest example of this being his pronounced ideas about emancipation while also owning hundreds of slaves. He was also deeply in personal debt throughout his life, though he insisted on working toward the national debt being eradicated while he was in office. He often wrote different viewpoints to different audiences, holding both sides to be his own opinion - an example being a book he wrote to be published in America warning young men about the many moral failings and pitfalls of French culture, while highly praising everything about France to others. <br /><br />At first blush this all comes off as hypocritical and disingenuous, and while I do agree on many cases, I have also seen firsthand examples of similar personality traits on a smaller scale and I think I have a better understanding of it now. It is actually, quite simply, a very common trait in introverts to agree with whomever they are speaking with or addressing, even if it's not exactly true to what they actually believe. <br /><br /> Ellis does a pretty good job of explaining this in the book, and he sums it up best by saying (not an exact quote) "whenever he had to choose between candor and courtesy, Jefferson almost always chose courtesy." <br /><br />I first heard of this concept in the book "Quiet: the power of introverts in a world that won't stop talking" and it truly changed my understanding of how the introverts in my life interacted. It explained why my husband always seems to agree with my parents' completely opposing political viewpoints, when I know it's not what he actually thinks. He's just trying to be polite and make the other person feel comfortable. It's not worth the personal discomfort of an argument or a confrontation to him, especially when he knows he's not going to change anyone's mind. <br /><br />This is a foreign concept to me, an extrovert who isn't afraid to speak her mind, even when my opinion isn't asked for(this is why Adams and I get along so well), but it does kind of make sense and it's probably kinder to think of introverts as trying to make people feel comfortable rather than thinking of them as deceitful liars. <br /><br />At any rate, despite all that, I still don't really like Jefferson, and I actually rather pity him. He was an introvert in a highly public office who *knew* slavery was wrong, but couldn't figure out what to realistically do about it and never took a real stand against it. He idealized a country with very little internal government presence, hoping that people could govern themselves and he died after seeing that utopian fantasy ingloriously smashed when he tried to implement it purely in the University he founded (several students got drunk and attacked faculty members). He also left his heirs with nothing because he never managed to ever get his personal debt under control. <br /><br />Maybe I'm being too hard on Mr. Jefferson here, but I think his legacy can take it, considering that the majority of people won't ever really know all this about him and will instead simply honor the man they imagine that he was.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7748156007931066879" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


