    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_569966296" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/569966296" />
    <a title="Adam Irving" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6043581-adam-irving"><img alt="Adam Irving" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1549515929p2/6043581.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/569966296?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam Irving" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam Irving" href="/user/show/6043581-adam-irving">Adam Irving</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer569966296" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10234401744213264995">I find myself a little disappointed by a lot of the reviews for this book. A lot of the complaints and critiques seem to center around the fact that this does not end up being the book they wished it would be, which is sort of absurd to begin with. This isn&apos;t a traditional biography, as the subtitle of the book makes abundantly clear. It is not a character assassination either. Ellis presents a character study via several historical vignettes. I found his presentation of Jefferson as a complicat</span>
  <span id="freeText10234401744213264995" style="display:none">I find myself a little disappointed by a lot of the reviews for this book. A lot of the complaints and critiques seem to center around the fact that this does not end up being the book they wished it would be, which is sort of absurd to begin with. This isn't a traditional biography, as the subtitle of the book makes abundantly clear. It is not a character assassination either. Ellis presents a character study via several historical vignettes. I found his presentation of Jefferson as a complicated man with faults, losses as well as victories. It de-mythologizes him, which I think is needed. It can become easy to lionize the revolutionary generation because of the distance in history, and I like that Ellis draws attention to this right along side talking about his achievements. We may not like for our heroes to have cracks, but it's an important reminder. This book does not have a political agenda either. It does address how Jefferson can be looked at from our space in time now, and it connects the Jeffersonian spirit to multiple political parties now (or circa late 90s). He is not especially gentle with either side of the aisle. Ultimately, this is a well written character study involving an icon of early American history. It delves into both his political and personal lives to find out what kind of person he is, or at least as much as we can know today from current records. The engaging style renders it easily accessible too. I generally do not care much for early American history, but this book makes me want to seek out the author's books on Adams and Washington.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10234401744213264995" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

